{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17595061","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17595061"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T10:58:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T10:58:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15333"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15333","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15333"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.83,0,0.1,0.07,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8024"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69328"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8024","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8024"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15333"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54781"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8755"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19497"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19499"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69328","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69328"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EChronic liver disease progresses through stages from inflammation to fibrosis and ultimately cirrhosis. Initially, patients with cirrhosis may be asymptomatic despite significant liver damage.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a complication indicating progression from compensated to decompensated cirrhosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oesophageal variceal bleeding","Improved synthetic function","Decreased portal pressure","Normal serum albumin","Reduced serum ammonia"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe progression from compensated to decompensated cirrhosis is marked by the development of complications. \u003Cstrong\u003EOesophageal variceal bleeding\u003C/strong\u003E is a serious complication resulting from portal hypertension and indicates decompensation. Other signs of decompensation include ascites, hepatic encephalopathy and jaundice.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImproved synthetic function\u003C/strong\u003E - Liver synthetic function worsens with disease progression, leading to coagulopathy and hypoalbuminaemia\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased portal pressure\u003C/strong\u003E - Portal pressure increases as cirrhosis progresses\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENormal serum albumin\u003C/strong\u003E - Albumin production decreases as hepatic function deteriorates\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduced serum ammonia\u003C/strong\u003E - Ammonia levels typically increase due to reduced hepatic clearance, contributing to encephalopathy\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe development of any of these complications marks the transition to decompensated cirrhosis and is associated with significantly reduced survival.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Decompensated cirrhosis manifests with complications including variceal bleeding, ascites, hepatic encephalopathy, jaundice and coagulopathy","Portal hypertension drives most complications in decompensated cirrhosis","The transition from compensated to decompensated cirrhosis indicates worsening liver function and poorer prognosis"],"references":["Joseph A, Samant H. Jaundice. 2023 Aug 8. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 31334972","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Gasmi B, Kleiner DE. Liver Histology: Diagnostic and Prognostic Features. Clin Liver Dis. 2020 Feb;24(1):61-74. doi: 10.1016/j.cld.2019.09.004. Epub 2019 Oct 31. PMID: 31753251; PMCID: PMC6986808"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54781"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15333"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54781","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54781"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-11T19:47:34+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-11T19:52:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8024"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69328"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relatio